A B S T R A C T
With the rise in the capabilities of language models, dense vector retrieval has grown in impor-
tance in the realm of information retrieval. This paper addresses the challenges faced by dense
retrieval models, especially the ineciencies from the use of high-dimensional embeddings.
The paper introduces a method to expedite similarity searches over large corpus embeddings by
leveraging a hierarchical clustering strategy. This approach achieves faster search times at the
cost of some accuracy. It builds upon the Dense Passage Retrieval (DPR) model and employs
the cc-news dataset and bert-base model from Huggingface for testing. The paper oers a deep
dive into various algorithms and tree-building strategies, juxtaposing them in terms of speed and
accuracy. The paper also provides a detailed benchmark result of the comparison between the
hierarchical clustering tree and other popular similarity search algorithms.
1. Introduction
With the improvement of the information extraction ability of language models, dense vector retrieval is playing
a more and more important role in the information retrieval eld. Nowadays, the adoption of dense retrieval models
has become indispensable for successful search engines. Notably, Google has incorporated BERT (Devlin, Chang, Lee
and Toutanova, 2019) as the foundation of its information retrieval model, while Facebook relies on the Faiss (Jgou,
Douze, Johnson, Hosseini and Deng, 2022) retrieval model, and Microsoft has introduced MT-DSSM (Guo, Fan,
Ai and Croft, 2016). The dense retrieval model can extract high-level understandings of natural language, which
make the search more accurate and easy to use. However, the eectiveness of dense vector retrieval models is
impeded by the challenge of sluggishness resulting from the use of high-dimensional embeddings, thereby hindering
the implementation of similarity search. Consequently, brute-force techniques are commonly used to traverse every
embedding, which makes retrieval speed signicantly lag behind that of traditional sparse vector retrieval models. In
traditional search algorithms like TF-IDF (Salton and Buckley, 1988) and BM25 (Robertson, Zaragoza et al., 2009),
the retrieval targets are the calculated values between searched token and documents, which means only documents
containing the searched words are selected and compared. In contrast, the dense vector retrieval model operates
dierently. Here, each document is accompanied by a high-dimensional dense vector embedding, forcing comparisons
to be performed across the entire corpus dataset. It will be super expansive when running a large dataset. According
to two pieces of research, dense passage retrieval is approximately 100 to 1000 times more computationally complex
than the traditional methods (Hofsttter and Hanbury, 2019; MacAvaney, Yates, Cohan and Goharian, 2019).
While algorithms like ColBERT (Khattab and Zaharia, 2020) and its variants (e.g., ColBERT-PRF (Wang,
MacDonald, Tonellotto and Ounis, 2023), ColBERTv2 (Santhanam, Khattab, Saad-Falcon, Potts and Zaharia, 2022),
etc.) are introduced to solve the retrieval speed problem from language models (LMs)s site, our objective, however, is
to enhance retrieval by accelerating the similarity search process.
Upon examining document embeddings, its evident that documents sharing similar themes often possess analogous
embedding vectors in high-dimensional spaces. A t-SNE (Van der Maaten and Hinton, 2008) visualization of
embeddings from a sample of 10000 corpus entries from our test dataset reveals that these embeddings naturally form
compact clusters. A comparison of the distribution of corpus embeddings versus random data can be seen in Figure 1.
This clustering tendency of the embeddings provides an avenue for introducing our proposed algorithm.
Accordingly, in this paper, we are introducing a solution for quicker similarity search over large corpus embeddings
by sacricing a little accuracy. We achieved the speed boost by building a search tree over the entire dataset using a

The following parts of this paper will be organized as follows: In Section 2, we will rst review the current
algorithms for similarity search over high-dimensional data. Subsequently, in Section 3, we will explicate our algorithm
in a meticulous manner while undertaking a thorough analysis of the associated hyper-parameters and their respective
inuences. Furthermore, in Section 4, we will benchmark our test implementation and establish a comparative

2. Literature review
The target of vector retrieval is, given a vector, an algorithm needs to nd the nearest neighbor(s) of that vector.
Many space partitioning methods, of which the main goal is to build some structure in the vector space, like
Grid File (Nievergelt, Hinterberger and Sevcik, 1984), KD Tree (Bentley, 1975), K-D-B Tree (Robinson, 1981), M
Tree (Ciaccia, Patella and Zezula, 1997), Ball Tree (Omohundro, 1989), have been studied to improve the speed
of vector retrieval speed. The diculty this algorithm faces is that the vectors are naturally unstructured data and
the curse of dimensionality their performance drastically declines with the increase of the dimensionality, because
of the dimensionality the algorithm introduced increases with the increase of dimension space (Weber, Schek and
Blott, 1998). The diculties can be understood from two perspective. The rst perspective is that the increase in
dimensionality will make the possible partition of the space increase exponentially. Or, another perspective is that the
tree structure created by partitioning the space will become very empty, and deep, greatly limiting the eciency of
the retrieval process. Another direction of ecient vector retrieval is to make local sensitivity hashing. To counter the
disadvantage introduced by high dimensionality, some studies suggest the usage of hashing, like Local Sensitivity
Hashing (LSH) (Indyk and Motwani, 1998). One great advantage of LSH is that when indexing the vectors, the
complexity of the index does not directly correspond to the dimensionality of the original vectors. However, to achieve
an accurate approximation of the nearest neighbor in high-dimension space, many more tables and a longer hash is
required, negatively inuencing the performance (Wang, Cao, Shu and Raei, 2013). However, it is still very promising
and is widely adopted, like in Spotifys Approximate Nearest Neighbour Oh Yeah (ANNOY) library
3
. Despite the
ANNOY utilizing the tree structure or forest structure, it resembles the LSH by adopting the concept of predened
amount of hyperplane to slice the space, essentially creating a hash-like bucket. Besides tree and hashing, another

potential solution is the graph. The primitive graph algorithm constructs a directional linked node, using an edge
that contains vector info. The vector info describes the direction and distance between two vectors in the space,
essentially linking two nodes (vectors) together. When conducting the search, the algorithm will greedily follow the
path that minimizes the distance between the input vector and indexed vectors in the database until the distance
no longer decreases. This primitive algorithm is not good for clustered data and may yield bad accuracy because
of local minimum, rather than the global one, is reached. To counter this problem, the current state-of-art vector
search algorithm is to use a hierarchical directional graph. Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds (HNSW) (Malkov
and Yashunin, 2016) is applied by Facebook (Meta)s vector search library, Faiss. The original idea of HNSW is from
skip list data structure (Pugh, 1990). Skip list essentially is a probabilistic data structure that consists of a hierarchy of
linked lists with nodes that contain forward pointers, allowing for ecient navigation between elements. The height
of each node is determined randomly, with higher nodes representing fewer elements and enabling faster searches.
Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds, unlike a 1-dimensional skip list, can more eciently deal with high dimensional
vectors, promising better overall performance than existing algorithms.
Besides trying to make the search itself more ecient, a previous study also suggests making the vector itself
more ecient, by doing product quantization (Jgou, Douze and Schmid, 2011). Product quantization is a technique
used for compressing data. It involves dividing the data into smaller subspaces or "cells" and quantizing each subspace
separately. The resulting quantized vectors can then be indexed and searched eciently, reducing the storage and
computation requirements. However, unlike principle component analysis, product quantization does not compress the
dimension of the vector, instead, it compresses the scope of the vectors. Consequently, the algorithm is also capable
of accelerating vector retrieval at the expanse of accuracy.
In recent times, there has been a surge in new strategies to enhance similarity search algorithms. As the predominant
similarity search algorithm, KD-tree has undergone numerous revisions, leading to the development of various
versions (Chen, Zhou, Tang, Singh, Bouguila, Wang, Wang and Du, 2019; Cai, Xu and Zhang, 2021; Cao, Wang, Zhao,
Duan and Zhang, 2020). Additionally, advancements have been made in information retrieval through the rened ball
tree (Fu, Zhuang, Chen, Guo and Wang, 2020) and LSH (Zheng, Xi, Weng, Hung, Liu and Jensen, 2020) methods.
As discussed above, KD-tree is suitable for low to medium-dimensional spaces but struggles with high-dimensional
data. ANNOY and HNSW, on the other hand, sacrice accuracy for speed. ANNOY constructs a forest of random
projection trees, while HNSW builds a hierarchical graph structure. In the case of DPR, the large dataset makes
ANNOY struggle with hashing conict and HNSW can not handle dynamic data properly and consumes a huge
memory. Even with the emergence of enhanced algorithm variants, these inherent issues persist.
Our approach is to build a tree by using hierarchical clustering, which can give a speed boost by sacricing accuracy.
Unlike KD-tree, the hierarchical clustering trees performance does not relate to the dimensionality of the data, making
it suitable for embeddings generated by BERT. Also, the ANNOYs drawback of dealing with a large dataset does not
exist in the traditional search tree structure we are using. Finally, by maintaining a tree structure, our approach has the
capability of dealing with dynamic data without re-initializing unless the change is not too big.
3. The proposed method
In order to realize faster information retrieval, we build a search tree over the entire dataset by using hierarchical
clustering. The clustering process proceeded top-down over the dataset recursively and nally constructed a tree
structure that can be used for faster retrieval.
Constructing the search tree may compromise the accuracy of the similarity search because the primary objective
is to identify similar instances rather than exact matches. While a search tree ensures the retrieval of similar results,
it cannot guarantee the absence of superior results in alternative branches. However, a search tree can signicantly
decrease the time complexity, and whats more, usually the approximate results are enough for search engines, which
means the loss of accuracy is acceptable if it can really accelerate the search. Accordingly, as shown in Figure 2,
we delineate the tree construction process which is categorized into three pivotal steps: similarity measurement,
clustering, and termination.
For the initiation of the search tree construction, the embeddings produced by the language models are to be
provided. Following this, a similarity metric for the entire set of embeddings must be established. This is pivotal
as the trees architecture is founded on the similarity between vectors. We suggest utilizing the dot product for this
purpose. During each hierarchical level of the tree, a clustering algorithm is applied to the document embeddings,
which subsequently generates child nodes representing clusters of similar documents. The growth of the tree persists

until the pre-established termination criterion is satised. In the following, we will introduce our proposed method in
detail.
3.1. Measuring Similarity
Before starting clustering and constructing the tree, we rst need to calculate the distance between dots to perform
clustering. Just like the original DPRs strategy, we use the dot product as the similarity between embeddings.
Compared to other popular distance measurements such as Euclidean distance and cosine similarity, the dot product
provides less bias and a relatively faster speed.
For retrieval accuracy, we did several rounds of experiments on the three dierent measurements. For each
similarity measurement, we retrieved the top 5 most similar results for the input query, and let users rate the retrieval
quality. The users feedback shows that both dot-product and cosine similarity give relatively good search results
compared to Euclidean distance.
Despite the notable ecacy of cosine similarity, it has certain theoretical limitations when compared to the dot
product. One primary concern is that cosine similarity normalizes vectors, making the algorithm sensitive only to
vector direction and not their magnitude. This can potentially omit a signicant data dimension if the magnitudes of
embeddings are meaningful. For instance, two embeddings distant in Euclidean space can appear proximate when
measured using cosine distance. Other problems of cosine distance such as high computational complexity and zero
vector problem also suggest dot product is a better choice.
While the dot product gives an overall better performance, other similarity measurements might be more
appropriate depending on the context and requirement. For example, Euclidean distance can become a better choice
when computational speed is a paramount concern.
3.2. Clustering
After computing the distances between document embeddings, we applied a clustering algorithm to categorize
the documents. The entire corpus serves as the root node of the tree, with each category representing a child node
branching from the root. Yet, this step presents multiple considerations. For instance, determining the number of child
nodes a parent should have, which translates to the number of clusters a node should be divided into, and selecting the
most appropriate clustering strategy. When constructing the tree, we can either make the K-xed or dynamic.
Generally speaking, the K decides the number of children nodes a node can have. It inuences the depth of the tree,
which directly relates to the speed and accuracy of the tree structure. The smaller the K, the fewer the children nodes
for every node, the deeper the tree, the faster the search speed, and the lower the accuracy. Vise versa. The decision of
the K value introduced the speed-accuracy trade-o, which is a crucial concept in the model-building process.
Here are two options for K-choosing strategies:
Lou et al.: Preprint submitted to Elsevier Page 4 of 11
Dense retrieval with hierarchical clustering
Fixed K: Using a xed K means determining the K value prior to tree construction, ensuring that K remains
constant throughout the tree. For example, setting K to 2 results in a binary tree, which is typically the quickest
but least precise. One way to optimize this is by pre-determining the K value and limiting the trees depth to
ensure accuracy remains within an acceptable range. However, the xed K approach has its drawbacks. A pre-
determined K value may not t the natural clustering tendencies in the data, leading to increased inaccuracies.
Dynamic K: The dynamic K approach determines the K value for each node individually during tree construc-
tion, allowing for varying K values across nodes. This oers greater tree exibility and can reduce inaccuracies
caused by incorrect clustering. In theory, the dynamic K-selection strategy strikes a balance between speed and
accuracy, outperforming the xed K method. To manage the trees structure, we can introduce a parameter,
Alpha, indicating the algorithms inclination to deepen the tree. The exact mathematical representation of Alpha
would be contingent on the specic clustering algorithm employed.
Figure 3: Dierent k-choosing-strategy result in dierent search trees
Figure 3 shows how the K-choosing strategy inuences the tree structure. A xed K strategy, exemplied by binary
trees, ensures consistent retrieval speed by prioritizing eciency. In contrast, a xed-depth tree oers better control
over retrieval accuracy, since there is a general trend of decreased accuracy as tree depth increases. The dynamic K
strategy introduces an element of exibility to the tree structure, oering a compromise between the predictability of
xed K and the accuracy control of xed depth. While it involves a reduction in user control over the trees architecture,
the dynamic K strategy strikes a balance between retrieval speed and accuracy.
After choosing the strategy for K, the clustering algorithm also needs to be declared. The clustering method controls
how we do the clustering, which is the key element for tree construction. Dierent clustering methods might result
in dierent search accuracy but have no inuence on the searchs time complexity. Here are the options for clustering
algorithms:
K-means: K-means is a widely used centroid-based clustering algorithm that aims to minimize the sum of
squared distances between data points and their assigned cluster centroids. It is well-known and easy to
implement.
K-mediods: K-medoids is one alternative solution for K-means. Instead of using centroids, k-medoids use
actual data points within the cluster as representatives. This makes k-medoids more robust to outliers. In high-
dimensional datasets, outliers are more likely to appear since the high-dimensional space makes the dataset more
sparse. So in our case, the K-medoids algorithm is theoretically more reliable than K-means.
Lou et al.: Preprint submitted to Elsevier Page 5 of 11
Dense retrieval with hierarchical clustering
Mean shift clustering: Mean shift is a non-parametric algorithm that doesnt require specifying the number of
clusters in advance. It makes mean shift clustering t the concept of our tree-building model pretty well since
it does not require the K-choosing strategy and the Alpha hyper-parameters, which makes the model easier to
adjust. However, it has a weak tolerance to high dimensionality since it is based on the density of data points, and
the density over high dimensional data is not very reliable. Dimensionality reduction might need to be performed
rst before applying this method.
Density peaks clustering: The density peaks clustering (DPC) (Rodriguez and Laio, 2014) has become popular
in recent years, and several benchmarks show its advantages in high-dimensional data (Cao, Zhao and Wang,
2023; Javed, Lee and Rizzo, 2020), which ts our needs very well. Furthermore, a synthesis of insights from
several studies (Chen, Hu, Fan, Shen, Zhang, Liu, Du, Li, Chen and Li, 2020; Du, Ding and Jia, 2016; Shan,
Li, Li, Cui, Li, Zhou and Li, 2022) underscores the enhanced performance achieved by integrating k-Nearest
Neighbors (kNN) with DPC, marking a convergence of speed, accuracy, and eciency in data clustering and
retrieval.
Figure 4: How to choose the clustering algorithm
Figure 4 provides a guidance on selecting the appropriate algorithm based on specic conditions. Generally
speaking, employing a dynamic k-selection strategy tends to yield better accuracy and the use of dimensionality
reduction can enhance the performance of clustering algorithms. Unless there are specic requirements to maintain a
particular tree structure or constraints against using dimensionality reduction, mean shift clustering and density peaks
clustering are preferred.
3.3. Termination strategy
After the similarity measurement and nishing the clustering, now the embeddings can be recursively divided,
allowing the tree to continuously expand.
The nal consideration is termination. Continual division of the dataset isnt feasible, especially in our dense
passage retrieval task. The search tree should be capable of returning not just the most similar document but a collection
of similar ones. Therefore, there must be a stopping condition for the data division to ensure that clusters at the
leaf nodes dont become too small. Without a termination criterion, each leaf node would end up containing only
Lou et al.: Preprint submitted to Elsevier Page 6 of 11
Dense retrieval with hierarchical clustering
a single document. When determining whether to continue subdividing a node, two primary factors should be taken
into account:
Loss: The loss of evaluating a node as a single cluster can give useful suggestions on whether a node needs
to be further divided or not. If a node encompasses predominantly similar data points, indicating it forms a
coherent cluster, splitting it further might reduce retrieval accuracy. This is because a relevant data point could
be misallocated to a dierent sub-cluster. On the other hand, a signicant loss when evaluated as a single cluster
suggests that the node should probably be subdivided further.
Size: The size of a node is equally crucial when considering termination. A small node shouldnt necessarily be
split, even if it doesnt form a well-dened cluster. Conversely, from a performance perspective, a particularly
large node might warrant further subdivision into more manageable portions, even if its associated loss is
minimal.
Owing to these termination considerations, the tree no longer remains a complete-tree structure (some branches
can be deep while others can be shallow). As a result, retrieval speed may vary, falling within a range rather than a
xed value, depending on whether the search path is shorter or longer.
4. Performance evaluation
We implement the benchmark to test the performance of the hierarchical clustering strategy for the dense embedding
retrieval task. We use the naive binary tree model, with K-means as the clustering method and Euclidean distance as
the similarity measurement as the base model for demonstration. A naive Python implementation was applied for the
benchmark, without any internal or external optimizations.
For the benchmark test, 10,000 embeddings are generated using the BERT-base model, each derived from the
CC-News dataset. Each of these embeddings is characterized as a 768-dimensional vector.

retrieval speed, which is compatible with some fully optimized C++ implementations. However, the K-means Tree is
the slowest one in indexing, potentially because of the recursive clustering operations.

Figure 5: Speed-Accuracy trade-o
Table 3 gives the inuence of dierent termination strategies. The size entry means that the k-means tree will stop
growing when it reaches the depth that the number of leaves on one node will be less than a set value, and in this case, it
is set to 50. The loss entry means that the k-means-tree will stop growing when the leaves in one node are very closely
clustered together, and the Euclidean distance threshold is reached. The Hybrid method is when the tree stops growth
if and only if the former two requirements are met. In the test, the hybrid strategies outperform both sized-based and
loss-based algorithms. It gives relatively shallower tree depth but quicker retrieval time, which indicates better tree
structure (a more complete tree).
The trade-o between speed and accuracy is shown in Figure 5. The blue line and the orange line represent the
indexing time and the retrieval time respectively, and the green curve represents the accuracy. The x-axis, labeled as
size, signies the value of the size-based termination strategy. A larger size corresponds to a shallower search tree. As
observed from the gure, a shallower tree results in reduced indexing time but increased retrieval time. Additionally,
as the tree becomes shallower, accuracy generally improves. At very large sizes, the search tree essentially degraded
to a naive search solution, where the indexing time is less than the retrieval time and accuracy reaches 100%.

Figure 6: Accuracy and dimensionality of data
Aiming to improve retrieval speeds in DPR, we work with high-dimensional embeddings. However, high
dimensionality will reduce the tendency to form clusters, especially when using a basic method like K-means in our
test. Given this scenario, its natural to consider dimensionality reduction. We employed T-SNE for this purpose and
constructed a search tree on the reduced dataset. The results indicate a direct correlation: the more we reduce the
dimensionality, the higher the overall accuracy of the search tree. This suggests that high dimensionality confuses
the clustering algorithms a lot. Refer to Figure 6 for the test results. Although the loss of information caused by
dimensionality reduction might potentially inuence the retrieval result, it still shows a potential solution for further
improving retrieval accuracy. Whats more, the curse of dimensionality in this case can also potentially be solved by
applying some clustering algorithms that exhibit high tolerance to high-dimensional data such as DBSCAN (Density-
Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) (Wang, Wu, Tang and Hor, 2015) or BIRCH (Balanced Iterative
Reducing and Clustering using Hierarchies) (Peng, Zheng, Xu, Lin and Leung, 2018).
5. Conclusion and Future Work
In this paper, we introduced an approach to expedite similarity searches across extensive corpus embeddings, which
entails a slight compromise in accuracy and memory. The trade-o between speed and accuracy depends on the specic
tree-building options being chosen, allowing exibility in tuning the model based on the requirements of the real usage
scenario. The benchmark result shows a signicant boost in the retrieval speed, even with the naive K-means Python
implementation. Whats more, the tree can keep growing deeper and gives nearly () retrieval speed by adjusting
the termination strategies if the user really wants to go extreme by sacricing more accuracy. While using a shallower
tree conguration, the accuracy is still compatible with other commonly used similarity search models.
A primary limitation of the hierarchical clustering model is its languid indexing speed, owing to the recurrent
execution of the clustering function. One potential remedy is to build the tree bottom-up rather than top-down, which
necessitates a single clustering operation. Whats more, some further consideration should be made when dealing with
data of super high dimensionality. By either using dimensionality reduction or choosing the clustering method that is
Lou et al.: Preprint submitted to Elsevier Page 9 of 11
Dense retrieval with hierarchical clustering
suitable for high dimensional data can largely prevent the loss of accuracy when dimensionality increases. Looking
ahead, we plan to conduct extensive benchmarks on larger datasets, explore additional tree-building alternatives, and
eliminate biases related to programming languages and libraries implementations.
